[In 1987-91, there were multiple outbreaks involving a wide range of
species in the South Luangwa National Park. In a severe epidemic in
2001, some 120 hippos (_Hippopotamus amphibius_) and 4 buffaloes
(_Syncercus caffer_) were reported dead of anthrax, but the actual
numbers were far greater, in the thousands. The aerial photographs of
the Luanga river showed dead hippos clogging the river and were
numbing. And that was just the dead hippos floating in the river. It
was believed that this epidemic was triggered by the population
quadrupling in number, which is both extremely stressful, with
fighting over the limited resources, and facilitates the spread of any
disease.

Readers are encouraged to see the series of postings on anthrax deaths
in the Ugandan Queen Elizabeth Park. It was clear in that region that
the situation was exacerbated by the hippo habit of scavenging their
own. This ensures that that it goes from the odd sporadic death to
being an epidemic, and it complicates any idea of control.

For a map of Zambia, see
http://www.un.org/Depts/Cartographic/map/profile/zambia.pdf. Chama
is in the northern portion of the province, near the border with
Malawi. For a closer look, go to
http://www.fallingrain.com/world/ZA/6/Chama.html. - Mod.MHJ]
